\begin_layout Subsection
Tangible Viewports Performance Evaluation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the Tangible Viewports system (Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:tangible-viewports"

\end_inset

), we have created a way for users to interact with tangible augmented objects
 in a similar way that they interact with them using a 3D view on a screen,
 with the added benefit of direct manipulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The exploratory study we conducted enabled us to validate that the metaphor
 seemed to work well enough so that all participants understood and interacted
 with the system without showing any sign of being destabilized by the chosen
 interaction technique; every user went on to work on their design without
 hesitations.
 However, it would be interesting to quantify the performance of the pointing
 technique compared to pointing on a 3D rendering inside a window.
 Moreover, it would also be worth comparing with the study done with CurSAR
 (Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:cursar"

\end_inset

).
 A lower decrease in completion time performance would point towards the
 hypothesis that the implicit coordinate system created screen bezel is
 important.
 From there, we could investigate ways to infer this coordinate system when
 using indirect pointing techniques in the real world as it was done in
 CurSAR.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Away from the Desktop, Towards the Desk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With CurSAR (Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:cursar"

\end_inset

) and Tangible Viewports (Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:tangible-viewports"

\end_inset

), we presented a working environment that leveraged the traditional ways
 to interact with digital information and combined it with real world objects
 and environments.
 More specifically, Tangible Viewports is an attempt at reducing the gap
 between the world of screens-based software and tangible objects.
 However, this approach has some limitations.
 Most notably is the constraint of having to position the physical object
 in front of the screen in order to interact with it using the mouse cursor.
 Following the general approach of ubiquitous computing and tangible interaction
, we think that fusing the desktop computer inside the desk it is laid on
 would be a promising direction.
 Of course, much work has already been done under the form of workbenches
 such as the pioneering work of Ullmer and Ishii with the metaDESK 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ullmer1997"

\end_inset

.
 However, it would be interesting to consider a workbench not as non-immersive
 virtual workspace, but as a real world work area onto which tools have
 both digital and physical purposes.
\end_layout

