\begin_layout Subsubsection
Peripheral Anamorphic Illusions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We discussed the use of anamorphic illusions in the introductory chapters
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:introduction"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:sar"

\end_inset

) and presented the working principle in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:sar-anamorphic-illusions"

\end_inset

.
 While not using the anamorphic principle to create a 3D illusion, we used
 the principles of perspective in the design of the hybrid widgets (Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:sar-hybrid-widgets"

\end_inset

) within the Tangible Viewports system.
 While we experimented with the design of these, we found out that it was
 uncomfortable the anamorphosis/perspective principle when you required
 the user to swicth his or her focus from the task to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

illusion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 back and forth.
 Instead, we think that these types of illusions could be leveraged when
 their purposes is meant to be working within the 
\emph on
periphery
\emph default
 of the user's field of view.
 It could potentially be used as ambient indicators or guides.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Anamorphic illusions typically do not work well at close distance.
 This is because of the stereo cues -- each eye is seeing a slightly different
 image, enabling the viewer to infer the depth of the objects in sight --
 that are strong when the observed objects are relatively close to the viewer.
 However, if the user is not focusing on the illusion itself, it might be
 possible to perceive it, even if it will obviously be blurry.
 Nevertheless, interesting uses of this principles could prove to be useful
 in certain interaction contexts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One example of such use in the context of the work presented in Part 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "part:interaction"

\end_inset

 of this thesis would be in trying to improve indirect pointing in the absence
 of a physical screen.
 Since a 2D window -- as it was used in Tangible Viewports -- acts like
 a good reference plane for interacting using a 2D indirect input devices,
 we could project a 3D illusion of a virtual window.
 Since it only acts like context for the cursor behavior, users might not
 have to put their focus on it.
 That way, it might be helpful in supporting hybrid operations -- that both
 leverage screen-based interactor and tangible augmented objects -- without
 having to deliberately position the physical object in front of the screen.
 Instead, we could render the 2D window outside the screen.
