\begin_layout Subsection
Fostering Wellbeing and Self-Reflection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the main underlying motivation while developing both Teegi and Tobe
 (respectively Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:teegi"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cha:tobe"

\end_inset

) was anchored in a desire to know more about our inner selves.
 Of course, physiological computing does not consists in an open door to
 the mind -- it is not possible to read thoughts.
 However, it consists in an interesting technological mean to gain insight
 about how our bodies and minds work.
 Interestingly, while demoing Tobe in a scientific museum and presenting
 the technology as a mean to know more about ourselves, one of the visitors
 stayed a moment to discuss it.
 She was emphasizing the fact that technology was unnecessarily and that
 introspection came from deliberate practice like meditation and contemplation.
 In that we agree.
 However, while not completely necessary, we believe that it can be a powerful
 tool to 
\emph on
support 
\emph default
and 
\emph on
encourage
\emph default
 meditative, contemplative and self-reflective practices.
 Some works have started to point in this direction, for example using conscious
 breathing patterns 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Moraveji2011,Moraveji2012"

\end_inset

.
 We also used this type of exercise with Tobe (Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:tobe-multi-users-relaxation"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One aspect we are very interested in is the combination of slow technology
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hallnas2001"

\end_inset

 and physiological computing.
 In the same way Weiser and Brown envisioned it 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
